@glindex shell/n
@code{shell/n} commands have a bug in Windows: if the environment variable SHELL is instantiated to some Windows shell implementation, then it is very possible that shell/@{1,2@} will not work, as it is always called with the -c flag to start the user command. For example, COMMAND.COM @strong{might} need the flag /C -- but there is no way to know a priori which command line option is necessary for every shell! It does not seems usual that Windows sets the SHELL environment variable: if it is not set, we set it up at startup time to point to the @code{sh.exe} provided with Ciao, which is able to start Windows aplications. Therefore, @code{?- shell('command.com').} just works.

@item
If 
@glindex exec/4
