@section Other information (@code{symfnames})

 The example discussed here is included in the distribution files. There is a main application file which uses module @code{mm}. This module reads a line from a file; the main predicate in the main file then prints this line. The important thing is that the file read is named by a symbolic name "@code{file}". The main application file declares another file where the symbolic names are assigned actual file names: 


@smallexample 

:- use_module(mm).

:- multifile alias_file/1.
alias_file(myfiles).

main :- p(X), display(X), nl.

@end smallexample  

Now, the file @code{myfiles.pl} can be used to change the file you want to read from without having to recompile the application. The current assignment is: 


@smallexample 

%:- use_package([]).
file_alias(file,'mm.pl').

@end smallexample  


@noindent
so the execution of the application will show the first line of @code{mm.pl}. However, you can change to: 


@smallexample 
file_alias(file,'main.pl').

@end smallexample  


@noindent
and then execution of the same executable will show the first line of @code{main.pl}. 
 



