@subsection The Dependency Rules 


@noindent
The package allows defining the following types of rules: 


@table @asis 


@item @code{@emph{TargetSuffix} <= @emph{SourceSuffix} :: @emph{SourceRoot} :- @emph{BodyLiterals}.} 

A rule of this form declares that in order to produce the file with suffix @emph{TargetSuffix} from a source file with the suffix @emph{SourceSuffix} and root name @emph{SourceRoot} the commands in @emph{BodyLiterals} must be executed. @emph{BodyLiterals} is a standard Ciao Prolog clause body, i.e., a comma-separated conjunction of literals. When writing the script, @emph{SourceRoot} is typically left as a variable, to be instantiated by 
@glindex lpmake
@code{lpmake} when the script is run to the root of name of the file to be processed. This allows using the value of @emph{SourceRoot} in @emph{BodyLiterals}. For example, the following rule: 


@smallexample 
:- use_module(library(terms),[atom_concat/2]).

dvi <= tex :: FileRoot :-
        atom_concat(['latex ',FileRoot,'.tex'],Command),
        system(Command).
@end smallexample  

states that we can generate a file @emph{File}@code{.dvi} if we have a file named @emph{File}@code{.tex} and that the command to do so is @code{latex }@emph{File}@code{.tex}. Thus, if this rule appears in file 
@glindex Makefile.pl
@code{Makefile.pl} and we issue the command @code{lpmake paper.dvi} the following occurs: 


@itemize @bullet{} 


@item If @code{paper.dvi} does not exist and @code{paper.tex} exists, then @code{paper.dvi} is generated from @code{paper.tex} by issuing the system command @code{latex paper.tex}. 


@item If @code{paper.dvi} already exists, nothing is done. 


@item If @code{paper.tex} does not exist, an error is reported. 


@end itemize  


@item @code{@emph{Target} <- :- @emph{BodyLiterals}.} 

A rule of this form declares that in order to produce the file @emph{Target} the commands in @emph{BodyLiterals} must be executed. @emph{Target} need not be a real file: it can also be simply the name of the rule, which is used to invoke it (as a procedure name). For example, the following rule, when the command @code{lpmake realclean} is issued, deletes temporary files in the LaTeX application: 


@smallexample 
:- use_module(library('make/system_extra')).

clean <- :-
        ls('*aux|*log|*~',Files)
        delete_files(Files).
@end smallexample  


@item @code{@emph{Target} <- @emph{Deps} :- @emph{BodyLiterals}.} 

A rule of this form declares that in order to produce the file @emph{Target}, first targets @emph{Deps} will be called (i.e., the elements of @emph{Deps} are either other targets with rules defined for them, or a file or files which are already present or which can --and will be-- generated from other available files using other rules). Then, the commands in @emph{BodyLiterals} will be executed. @emph{Deps} may be one target or a list of targets. For example, the following rule, when the command @code{lpmake realclean} is issued, cleans all the temporary files in the LaTeX application (including @code{.dvi} and @code{.ps} files). It requires that clean be executed first: 


@smallexample 
:- use_package(functions).
:- use_module(library('make/system_extra')).

realclean <- clean :-
        delete_files(~ls('*dvi|*ps')).
@end smallexample  

The following rule states that in order to meet the target @code{view}, target @code{paper.ps} must be available or generated. For example, @code{lpmake view} can be used to call the 
@glindex ghostview
@code{ghostview} visualizer on @code{paper.ps}. Note the use of a globally defined @emph{predicate} @code{main} which is called in two places in the rule, and could be used in other rules in the same file (@code{main := paper.} is equivalent to the fact @code{main(paper).} --see the 
@glindex functions
@code{functions} library): 


@smallexample 
:- use_package(functions).
:- use_module(library('make/system_extra')).
:- use_module(library(terms),[atom_concat/2]).

main := paper.

view <- ~atom_concat([~main,'.ps']) :-
        system(~atom_concat(['ghostview ',~main,'.ps'])).
@end smallexample  


@end table  

In addition to these rules, the configuration file can define normal predicates in the usual way, or import predicates from other modules, all of which can be called from the bodies of the dependency rules. For example, the 
@glindex system_extra
@code{system_extra} library (an extension of the 
@glindex system
@code{system} library) defines many system predicates in a form which makes them very useful inside 
@glindex Makefile
@code{Makefile}s, specially if the 
@glindex functions
@code{functions} package is used (see the examples below). 

If 
@glindex lpmake
@code{lpmake} is called without an explicit target as argument, then the first target rule in the Makefile is used. This is useful in that the first rule can be seen as the default rule. 



