@subsection Documenting Rules 


@noindent
It is also possible to define documentation for the rules: 


@table @asis 


@item @code{target_comment(@emph{Target}) :- @emph{BodyLiterals}.} 

A rule of this form allows documenting the actions related to the target. The body (@emph{BodyLiterals}) will be called in two circumstances: 


@itemize @bullet{} 


@item If @emph{Target} is called during execution of '@code{lpmake} @emph{commands}'. 


@item When calling '@code{lpmake -h}'. 


@end itemize  

Using noun forms (@emph{generation of foo} instead of @emph{generating foo}) in comments helps this dual purpose. For example, the following rule: 


@smallexample 
target_comment(realclean) :- 
        display('Cleanup of all generated files.').
@end smallexample  

will produce output in the two cases pointed out above. 


@item @code{dependency_comment(@emph{SourceSuffix},@emph{TargetSuffix},@emph{SourceRoot}) :- @emph{BodyLiterals}.} 

Same as the previous rule, but for suffix rules. See, for example, the following generic rule: 


@smallexample 
:- use_module(library(terms),[atom_concat/2]).

dependency_comment(SSuffix,TSuffix,FileBase) :- 
        display(~atom_concat(['Generation of ',FileBase,'.',TSuffix,
                              ' from ',FileBase,'.',SSuffix])).
@end smallexample  


@end table  



