@deffn DECLARATION index/1:






@strong{Usage:} :- @code{index(IndexSpecs)}.
@itemize @minus
@item @emph{Description:} Declares an indexing scheme for a predicate. All specs of @code{IndexSpecs} must be terms for the same predicate. Each spec declares an indexing on a combination of the arguments. Indexing will be performed using any of the specs in @code{IndexSpecs} (being thus interpreted as an or). 

You should use a @code{*} in an argument position if you wish to hash on the entire term in that argument. If a @code{+} is used only one level of the term in the argument is used for hashing. An @code{i} is used to indicate that argument is already an integer, and therefore its own value will be used for hashing. The argspec @code{?} simply indicates not to use the argument for indexing. 

For example, the index specification: 
@smallexample 
:- index foo(+,?,*,i), foo(?,?,?,i).
@end smallexample  
declares indexing for @code{foo/4} either on a combination of the first, third, and fourht arguments, or only on the last argument, which is an integer. In the first case, only the principal functor of the first argument will be used for hashing; the third argument will be used in its entirety. 

The argspec @code{n} is a pragmatic extension and can not be used in conjunction with the other specifiers aside from @code{?}. It stands for "nonvar" and implies that the argument will not be used for hashing, since only ground terms can effectively be used in hashing. Thus, it can not be used in combination with other specifiers within a particular index specification. It is often the fastest thing to use.  
