@subsection Term construction 

All term construction primitives return an argument of type @code{ciao_term}, which is the result of constructing a term. All Ciao Prolog terms can be built using the interface operations @code{ciao_var()}, @code{ciao_structure()}, @code{ciao_integer()}, and @code{ciao_float()}. There are, however, variants and specialized versions of these operations which can be freely intermixed. Using one version or another is a matter of taste and convenience. We list below the prototypes of the primitives in order of complexity. 

Throughout this section, @strong{true}, when referred to a boolean value, correspond to the integer value @code{1}, and @strong{false} correspond to the integer value @code{0}, as is customary in C boolean expressions. These values also available as the (predefined) constants @code{ciao_true} and @code{ciao_false}, both of type @code{ciao_bool}. 


@itemize @bullet{} 
@item @code{ciao_term ciao_var();} 

Returns a fresh, unbound variable. 


@item @code{ciao_term ciao_integer(int i);} 

Creates a term, representing an integer from the Prolog point of view, from a C integer. 


@item @code{ciao_term ciao_float(double i);} 

Creates a term, representing a floating point number, from a floating point number. 


@item @code{ciao_term ciao_put_number_chars(char *number_string);} 

It converts @code{number_string} (which must a string representing a syntactically valid number) into a @code{ciao_term}. 


@item @code{ciao_term ciao_atom(char *name);} 

Creates an atom whose printable name is given as a C string. 


@item @code{ciao_term ciao_structure_a(char *name, int arity, ciao_term *args);} 

Creates a structure with name 'name' (i.e., the functor name ), arity 'arity' and the components of the array 'args' as arguments: @code{args[0]} will be the first argument, @code{args[1]} the second, and so on. The 'args' array itself is not needed after the term is created, and can thus be a variable local to a procedure. An atom can be represented as a 0-arity structure (with @code{ciao_structure(name, 0)}), and a list cell can be constructed using the '.'/2 structure name. The @code{_a} suffix stands for @emph{array}. 
 
@item @code{ciao_term ciao_structure(char *name, int arity, ...);} 

Similar to ciao_structure_a, but the C arguments after the arity are used to fill in the arguments of the structure. 
 
@item @code{ciao_term ciao_list(ciao_term head, ciao_term tail);} 

Creates a list from a @code{head} and a @code{tail}. It is equivalent to @code{ciao_structure(".", 2, head, tail)}. 
 
@item @code{ciao_term ciao_empty_list();} 

Creates an empty list. It is equivalent to @code{ciao_atom("[]")}. 


@item @code{ciao_term ciao_listn_a(int len, ciao_term *args);} 

Creates a list with 'len' elements from the array @code{args}. The @emph{nth} element of the list (starting at 1) is @code{args[n-1]} (starting at zero). 


@item @code{ciao_term ciao_listn(int length, ...);} 

Like @code{ciao_listn_a()}, but the list elements appear explicitly as arguments in the call. 


@item @code{ciao_term ciao_dlist_a(int len, ciao_term *args, ciao_term base);} 

Like @code{ciao_listn_a}, but a difference list is created. @code{base} whill be used as the tail of the list, instead of the empty list. 


@item @code{ciao_term ciao_dlist(int length, ...);} 

Similar to @code{ciao_dlist_a()} with a variable number of arguments. The last one is the tail of the list. 


@item @code{ciao_term ciao_copy_term(ciao_term src_term);} 

Returns a new copy of the @code{term}, with fresh variables (as @code{copy_term/2} does). 


@end itemize  
 

