@comment node-name, next,  previous,  up
@subsection Testing the Type of a Term 

A @code{ciao_term} can contain @emph{any} Prolog term, and its implementation is opaque to the C code. Therefore the only way to know reliably what data is passed on is using explicit functions to test term types. Below, @code{ciao_bool} is a type defined in @code{"ciao_prolog.h"} which can take the values 1 (for @strong{true}) and 0 (for @strong{false}). 
 
@itemize @bullet{} 
@item @code{ciao_bool ciao_is_variable(ciao_term term);} 

Returns true if @code{term} is currently an uninstantiated variable. 


@item @code{ciao_bool ciao_is_number(ciao_term term);} 

Returns true if @code{term} is an integer (of any length) or a floating point number. 


@item @code{ciao_bool ciao_is_integer(ciao_term term);} 

Returns true if @code{term} is instantiated to an integer. 


@item @code{ciao_bool ciao_fits_in_int(ciao_term term);} 

Returns true if @code{term} is instantiated to an integer which can be stored in an @code{int}, and false otherwise. 


@item @code{ciao_bool ciao_is_atom(ciao_term atom);} 

Returns true if @code{term} is an atom. 


@item @code{ciao_bool ciao_is_list(ciao_term term);} 

Returns true if @code{term} is a list (actually, a @code{cons} cell). 


@item @code{ciao_bool ciao_is_empty_list(ciao_term term);} 

Returns true if @code{term} is the atom which represents the empty list (i.e., @code{[]}). 


@item @code{ciao_bool ciao_is_structure(ciao_term term);} 

Returns true if @code{term} is a structure of any arity. This includes atoms (i.e., structures of arity zero) and lists, but excludes variables and numbers. 


@end itemize  
 

@node Term navigation, Testing for Equality and Performing Unification, Testing the Type of a Term, Custom access to Prolog from C
@comment node-name, next,  previous,  up
@subsection Term navigation 

The functions below can be used to recover the value of a @code{ciao_term} into C variables, or to inspect Prolog structures. 
 
@itemize @bullet{} 


@item @code{int ciao_to_integer(ciao_term term); } 

Converts @code{term} to an integer. @code{ciao_is_integer(term)} must hold. 


@item @code{ciao_bool ciao_to_integer_check(ciao_term term, int *result); } 

Checks whether @code{term} fits into the size of an integer. If so, true is returned and @code{*result} is unified with the integer @code{term} represents. Otherwise, false is returned and @code{*result} is not touched. 


@item @code{double ciao_to_float(ciao_term term);} 

Converts @code{term} to a float value. @code{ciao_is_number(term)} must hold. 


@item @code{char *ciao_get_number_chars(ciao_term term);} 

It converts @code{ciao_term} (which must be instantiated to a number) into a C string representing the number in the current radix. The string returned is a copy, which must (eventually) be explicitly deallocated by the user C code using the operation @code{ciao_free()} 


@item @code{char *ciao_atom_name(ciao_term atom);} 

Returns the name of the atom. The returned string @emph{is the one internally used by Ciao Prolog}, and should not be deallocated, changed or altered in any form. The advantage of using it is that it is fast, as no data copying is needed. 


@item @code{char *ciao_atom_name_dup(ciao_term atom);} 

Obtains a @strong{copy} of the name of the atom. The string can be modified, and the programmer has the responsibility of deallocating it after being used. Due to the copy, it is slower than calling @code{char *ciao_atom_name()}. 


@item @code{ciao_term ciao_list_head(ciao_term term);} 

Extracts the head of the list @code{term}. Requires @code{term} to be a list. 


@item @code{ciao_term ciao_list_tail(ciao_term term);} 

Extracts the tail of the list @code{term}. Requires @code{term} to be a list. 


@item @code{char *ciao_structure_name(ciao_term term);} 

Extracts the name of the structure @code{term}. Requires @code{term} to be a structure. 


@item @code{int ciao_structure_arity(ciao_term term);} 

Extracts the arity of the structure @code{term}. 

Requires @code{term} to be a structure. 


@item @code{ciao_term ciao_structure_arg(ciao_term term, int n);} 

Extracts the @emph{nth} argument of the structure @code{term}. It behaves like @code{arg/3}, so the first argument has index 1. Requires @code{term} to be a structure. 


@end itemize  
 

