@subsection Calling Prolog from C 

It is also possible to make arbitraty calls to Prolog predicates from C. There are two basic ways of make a query, depending on whether only one solution is needed (or if the predicate to be called is known to generate only one solution), or if several solutions are required. 

When only one solution is needed @code{ciao_commit_call} obtains it (the solution obtained will obviously be the first one) and discards the resources used for finding it: 


@itemize @bullet{} 


@item @code{ciao_bool ciao_commit_call(char *name, int arity, ...);} 

Makes a call to a predicate and returns true or false depending on whether the query has succedeed or not. In case of success, the (possibly) instantiated variables are reachable from C. 


@item @code{ciao_bool ciao_commit_call_term(ciao_term goal);} 

Like @code{ciao_commit_call()} but uses the previously built term @code{goal} as goal. 


@end itemize  

If more than one solution is needed, it is necessary to use the @code{ciao_query} operations. A consult begins with a @code{ciao_query_begin} which returns a @code{ciao_query} object. Whenever an additional solution is required, the @code{ciao_query_next} function can be called. The query ends by calling @code{ciao_query_end} and all pending search branches are pruned. 


@itemize @bullet{} 


@item @code{ciao_query *ciao_query_begin(char *name, int arity, ...);} 

The predicate with the given name, arity and arguments (similar to the @code{ciao_structure()} operation) is transformed into a @code{ciao_query} object which can be used to make the actual query. 


@item @code{ciao_query *ciao_query_begin_term(ciao_term goal);} 

Like ciao_query_begin but using the term @code{goal} instead. 


@item @code{ciao_bool ciao_query_ok(ciao_query *query);} 

Determines whether the query may have pending solutions. A false return value means that there are no more solutions; a true return value means that there are more possible solutions. 
 
@item @code{void ciao_query_next(ciao_query *query);} 

Ask for a new solution. 


@item @code{void ciao_query_end(ciao_query *query);} 

Ends the query and frees the used resources. 


@end itemize  



