@subsection Mathematical functions 

In this example, the standard mathematical library is accessed to provide the @emph{sin}, @emph{cos}, and @emph{fabs} functions. Note that the library is specified simply as 


@smallexample 
:- use_foreign_library([m]).
@end smallexample  

The foreign interface adds the @code{-lm} at compile time. Note also how some additional options are added to optimize the compiled code (only glue code, in this case) and mathematics (only in the case of Linux in an Intel processor). 

@strong{File} @emph{math.pl}: 

:- module(math, [sin/2, cos/2, fabs/2], [foreign_interface]).

:- true pred sin(in(X),go(Y)) :: num * num + (foreign,returns(Y)).
:- true pred cos(in(X),go(Y)) :: num * num + (foreign,returns(Y)).
:- true pred fabs(in(X),go(Y)) :: num * num + (foreign,returns(Y)).

