The 
@glindex tcltk
@code{tcltk} library package is a bidirectional interface to the @emph{Tcl} language and the @emph{Tk} toolkit. Tcl is an interpreted scripting language with many extension packages, particularly the graphical interface toolkit, Tk. The interaction between both languages is expressed in terms of an interface between the Tcl/Tk process and the Prolog process. This approach allows the development of mixed applications where both sides, Tcl/Tk and Prolog, can be combined in order to exploit their respective capabilities. 

This library uses two sockets to connect both the Tcl and the Prolog processes: @emph{event_socket} and @emph{term_socket}. There are also two Tcl global variables: @emph{prolog_variables} and @emph{terms}. The value of any of the bound variables in a goal will be stored in the array @code{prolog_variables} with the variable name as index. @emph{Terms} is the string which contains the printed representation of prolog @emph{terms}. 
 


@noindent
@strong{Prolog to Tcl} 

The Tcl/Tk side waits for requests from the Prolog side, and executes the Tcl/Tk code received. Also, the Tcl/Tk side handles the events and exceptions which may be raised on its side, passing on control to the Prolog side in case it is necessary. 

To use Tcl, you must create a @emph{Tcl interpreter} object and send commands to it. A @emph{Tcl} command is specified as follows: 


@smallexample 
      Command         --> Atom  @{ other than [] @}
                        | Number
                        | chars(PrologString)
                        | write(Term)
                        | format(Fmt,Args)
                        | dq(Command)
                        | br(Command)
                        | sqb(Command)
                        | min(Command)
                        | ListOfCommands
      ListOfCommands  --> []
                        |[Command|ListOfCommands]
@end smallexample  

where: 


@table @asis 


@item @code{Atom} 
denotes the printed representation of the atom. 


@item @code{Number} 
denotes their printed representations. 


@item @code{chars(PrologString)} 
denotes the string represented by @emph{PrologString} (a list of character codes). 


@item @code{write(Term)} 
denotes the string that is printed by the corresponding built-in predicate. 


@item @code{format(Term)} 
denotes the string that is printed by the corresponding built-in predicate. 


@item @code{dq(Command)} 
denotes the string specified by @emph{Command}, enclosed in double quotes. 


@item @code{br(Command)} 
denotes the string specified by @emph{Command}, enclosed in braces. 


@item @code{sqb(Command)} 
denotes the string specified by @emph{Command}, enclosed in square brackets. 


@item @code{min(Command)} 
denotes the string specified by @emph{Command}, immediately preceded by a hyphen. 


@item @code{ListOfCommands} 
denotes the strings denoted by each element, separated by spaces. 


@end table  

The predicates to use Tcl from Prolog are 
@glindex tcl_new/1
@code{tcl_new/1}, 
@glindex tcl_delete/1
@code{tcl_delete/1}, 
@glindex tcl_eval/3
@code{tcl_eval/3}, and 
@glindex tcl_event/3
@code{tcl_event/3}. 


@noindent
An example of use with Prolog as master and Tcl as slave, consisting of a GUI to a program which calculates the factorial of a number: 


@noindent

@smallexample 
:- use_module(library(tcltk)).

go :-
        tcl_new(X),
        tcl_eval(X,[button,'.b',min(text),dq('Compute!')],_),
        tcl_eval(X,[button,'.c','-text',dq('Quit')],_),
        tcl_eval(X,[entry,'.e1',min(textvariable),'inputval'],_),
        tcl_eval(X,[label,'.l1',min(text),dq('The factorial of ')],_),
        tcl_eval(X,[pack, '.l1','.e1'],_),
        tcl_eval(X,[entry,'.e2',min(textvariable),'outputval'],_),
        tcl_eval(X,[label,'.l2',min(text),dq('is  ')],_),
        tcl_eval(X,[pack, '.l2','.e2'],_),
        tcl_eval(X,[pack,'.b','.c',min(side),'left'],_),
        tcl_eval(X,[bind,'.b','<ButtonPress-1>',
                    br([set,'inputval','$inputval','\n',
                    prolog_one_event,dq(write(execute(tk_test_aux:factorial('$inputval','Outputval')))),'\n',
                    set, 'outputval','$prolog_variables(Outputval)'])],_),
        tcl_eval(X,[bind,'.c','<ButtonPress-1>',
                    br([prolog_one_event,dq(write(execute(exit_tk_event_loop)))])],_),
        tk_event_loop(X).

@end smallexample  
 
@noindent
@strong{Tcl to Prolog} 

This is the usual way to build a GUI application. The slave, Prolog, behaves as a server that fulfills eventual requests from the master side, Tcl. At some point, during the user interaction with the GUI, an action may take place that triggers the execution of some procedure on the slave side (a form submit, for example). Thus, the slave is invoked, performs a service, and returns the result to the GUI through the socket connection. 

This library includes two main specific Tcl commands: 


@table @asis 


@item @code{prolog} @emph{Goal} 
@emph{Goal} is a string containing the printed representation of a Prolog goal. The goal will be called in the user module unless it is prefixed with another module name. The call is always deterministic and its can be either of the following: 


@table @asis 


@item @emph{1}, in case of success 
The value of any of the variables in the goal that is bound to a term will be returned to Tcl in the array prolog_variables with the variable name as index. 


@item @emph{0}, if the execution fails 
The Prolog exception Tcl exception is raised. The error message will be "Prolog Exception: " appended with a string representation of such exception. 


@end table  


@item @code{prolog_event} @emph{Term} 
Adds the new @emph{term} to the @emph{terms} queue. These can be later retrieved through predicates 
@glindex tcl_event/3
@code{tcl_event/3} and 
@glindex tk_next_event/2
@code{tk_next_event/2}. 


@end table  

Additionally, seven extra Tcl commands are defined. 


@table @asis 


@item @code{prolog_delete_event} 
Deletes the first @emph{term} of the @emph{terms} queue. 


@item @code{prolog_list_events} 
Sends all the @emph{terms} of the @emph{terms} queue through the @emph{event_socket}. The last element is @emph{end_of_event_list}. 


@item @code{prolog_cmd} @emph{Command} 
Receives as an argument the Tcl/Tk code, evaluates it and returns through the @emph{term_socket} the term @emph{tcl_error} in case of error or the term @emph{tcl_result} with the result of the command executed. If the command is @emph{prolog}, upon return, the goal run on the prolog side is received. In order to get the value of the variables, predicates are compared using the @emph{unify_term} command. Returns 0 when the sript runs without errors, and 1 if there is an error. 


@item @code{prolog_one_event} @emph{Term} 
Receives as an argument the @emph{term} associated to one of the Tk events. Sends the @emph{term} through the @emph{event_socket} and waits for its unification. Then @emph{unify_term} command is called to update the @emph{prolog_variables} array. 


@item @code{prolog_thread_event} @emph{Term} 
Receives as an argument the @emph{term} associated to one of the Tk events. Sends the @emph{term} through the @emph{event_socket} and waits for its unification. Then @emph{unify_term} command is called to update the @emph{prolog_variables} array. In this case the @emph{term_socket} is non blocking. 


@item @code{convert_variables} @emph{String} 
Its argument is a string containing symbols that can not be sent through the sockets. This procedure deletes them from the input string and returns the new string. 


@item @code{unify_term} @emph{Term1} @emph{Term2} 
Unifies @emph{Term1} and @emph{Term2} and updates the the @emph{prolog_variables} array. 


@end table  

The predicates to use Prolog from Tcl are 
@glindex tk_event_loop/1
@code{tk_event_loop/1}, 
@glindex tk_main_loop/1
@code{tk_main_loop/1}, 
@glindex tk_new/2
@code{tk_new/2}, and 
@glindex tk_next_event/2
@code{tk_next_event/2}. 


@noindent
An example of use with Tcl as master and Prolog as slave, implementing the well known "Hello, world!" dummy program (more can be seen in directory examples): 

Prolog side: 


@noindent

@smallexample 
:- use_module(library(tcltk)).
:- use_package(classic).
     
hello('Hello, world!').
     
go :-
        tk_new([name('Simple')], Tcl),
        tcl_eval(Tcl, 'source simple.tcl', _),
        tk_main_loop(Tcl),
        tcl_delete(Tcl).

@end smallexample  

