@section General operation 

To prepare to use 
@glindex lpmake
@code{lpmake}, and in a similar way to 
@glindex make
@code{make}, you must write a 
@coindex configuration file
@glindex configuration file
@emph{configuration file}: a module (typically called 
@glindex Makefile.pl
@code{Makefile.pl}) that describes the relationships among files in your program or application, and states the commands for updating each file. In a program, typically the executable file is updated from object files, which are in turn made by compiling source files. Another example is running 
@glindex latex
@code{latex} and 
@glindex dvips
@code{dvips} on a set of source @code{.tex} files to generate a document in @code{dvi} and @code{postscript} formats. Once a suitable makefile exists, each time you change some source files, simply typing @code{lpmake} suffices to perform all necessary operations (recompilations, processing text files, etc.). The 
@glindex lpmake
@code{lpmake} program uses the dependency rules in the makefile and the last modification times of the files to decide which of the files need to be updated. For each of those files, it issues the commands recorded in the makefile. For example, in the 
@glindex latex
@code{latex}/
@glindex dvips
@code{dvips} case one rule states that the @code{.dvi} file whould be updated from the @code{.tex} files whenever one of them changes and another rule states that the @code{.ps} file needs to be updated from a @code{.dvi} file every time it changes. The rules also describe the commands to be issued to update the files. 

So, the general process is as follows: 
@glindex lpmake
@code{lpmake} executes commands in the configuration file to update one or more target @emph{names}, where @emph{name} is often a program, but can also be a file to be generated or even a ``virtual'' target. 
@glindex lpmake
@code{lpmake} updates a target if it depends on prerequisite files that have been modified since the target was last modified, or if the target does not exist. You can provide command line arguments to 
@glindex lpmake
@code{lpmake} to control which files should be regenerated, or how. 



@node Format of the Configuration File, lpmake usage, General operation, The Ciao lpmake scripting facility
@comment node-name, next,  previous,  up
@section Format of the Configuration File 


@glindex lpmake
@code{lpmake} uses as default configuration file the file 
@glindex Makefile.pl
@code{Makefile.pl}, if it is present in the current directory. This can be overridden and another file used by means of the @code{-m} option. The configuration file must a @emph{module} that uses the 
@glindex make
@code{make} package. This package provides syntax for defining the dependency rules and functionality for correctly interpreting these rules. The configuration files can contain such rules and also arbitrary Ciao Prolog predicates. The syntax of the rules is described in @ref{The Ciao Make Package}, together with some examples. 



@node lpmake usage, Acknowledgments (lpmake), Format of the Configuration File, The Ciao lpmake scripting facility
@comment node-name, next,  previous,  up
@section lpmake usage 


@smallexample 


Supported command line options:

lpmake [-v] <command1> ... <commandn>

  Process commands <command1> ... <commandn>, using 
  file 'Makefile.pl' in the current directory as 
  configuration file. The configuration file must 
  be a module. This is useful to implement 
  inherintance across diferent configuration files, 
  i.e., the values declared in a configuration file 
  can be easily made to override those defined in 
  another.

  The optional argument '-v' produces verbose output, 
  reporting on the processing of the dependency rules. 
  Very useful for debugging Makefiles.

lpmake [-v] [-m <.../Configfile.pl>] <command1> ... <commandn>

  Same as above, but using file <.../Configfile.pl> 
  as configuration file. 

lpmake -h     [ -m <.../Configfile.pl> ]
lpmake -help  [ -m <.../Configfile.pl> ]

  Print this help message. If a configuration file is given, 
  and the commands in it are commented, then information on 
  these commands is also printed.


@end smallexample  





